author: The Columbus Dispatch
title: College football | For record 102nd time, Ohio State is No.1 in AP poll | Buckeye Xtra
text:
>> View 100 photos from the Buckeyes' latest victory 
Ohio State stayed atop both major-college football polls today, the record 102nd week the Buckeyes have been No. 1 in the 79-year history of the Associated Press poll.
Ohio State (6-0), coming off a 49-28 victory over Big Ten foe Maryland on Saturday, has been the only team to maintain its ranking this season in both the AP media poll and the Amway coaches poll. Along the way, it has pushed its nation’s best active winning streak to 19 games and its Big Ten regular-season victory streak to 26.
>>  Dispatch  sports editor Ray Stein answers your questions about Buckeyes football during our weekly chat, 1 p.m. Thursday, dispatch.com/osuchat 
Meanwhile, this week’s poll results are another good example of the chaos going on beneath the Buckeyes. TCU -- No.2 in both polls last week -- slipped to No.3 after a close call at Kansas State, while Big 12 counterpart Baylor moved to No.2 in both.
Michigan State, which escaped Rutgers on Saturday night, dropped one spot in the coaches poll to No.4. The rest of the top 10 are LSU, Clemson, Utah, Florida State, Alabama and Texas A&M.
MSU plummeted to seventh in the AP poll. Utah moved up a spot to fourth, followed by Clemson and LSU. Florida is No.8, Texas A&M ninth and Alabama 10th.
>> Got a question about Ohio State football? Ask the experts! 
Michigan moved to 12th in the AP, 14th in the coaches poll. The Wolverines will host Michigan State at 3:30 p.m. Saturday in a Big Ten East Division showdown. Ohio State hosts Penn State at 8 p.m. Saturday. The Nittany Lions took OSU to two overtimes last year before losing.
